Scaling

Scaling means increasing the system capacity to handle:

More users
More traffic
More data
More requests



Vertical Scaling

Vertical scaling means increasing the power of a single server/system by adding more resources.

Resources Added
More RAM
Faster CPU
More Storage
Better GPU
Example

A website server is slow.

Instead of adding many servers, we:

Upgrade from 8 GB RAM → 32 GB RAM
Upgrade CPU from 2 Core → 8 Core

Now the same server handles more users.

Real-Time Example
Small startup websites
College management systems
Small e-commerce websites

Example:
A MySQL database running on one machine becomes slow, so the company upgrades the machine configuration.

Advantages
Easy to implement
No major code changes
Simple maintenance
Disadvantages
Has hardware limit
Expensive after some point
If one server fails → whole system fails

1. Vertical Scaling

Increasing the power of the same server.

Example:

8 GB RAM → 32 GB RAM
2 Core CPU → 8 Core CPU
One Server → Bigger Server

2. Horizontal Scaling

Adding multiple servers instead of upgrading one server.

Example:

1 server → 5 servers
Load is shared among all servers
Server 1
Server 2
Server 3
Real-Time Example
Instagram / Netflix

When millions of users access the app:

One server is not enough
Multiple servers are added
Load balancer distributes traffic

This is called horizontal scaling.


